        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Input uncertainty bounded and documented with sensitivity analysis",
        "description": "All model inputs are characterized with stated uncertainty bounds. For inputs with wide uncertainty (blood viscosity ±18% across population), a one-at-a-time sensitivity study demonstrates that the RH ranking of operating points is preserved across the full uncertainty range."
      },
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity is the primary uncertain input, with a documented population-level range of ±18% (CV=0.11) derived from the blood-viscosity-population-survey dataset. This is an explicitly low-confidence input: the porcine blood analog used in validation does not fully capture in-vivo human variability. A one-at-a-time sensitivity analysis (viscosity varied across 5th–95th percentile of population distribution) confirms that the rank ordering of hemolysis across the 5 operating points is preserved in all cases, and the worst-case operating point identification is robust. The wide uncertainty bound is documented honestly; it does not invalidate the COU claim but is accepted as residual uncertainty given the compensating experimental validation. Gradation 2 achieved with this documented gap."
    },
